The Ellora Caves are a series of 34 rock-cut Buddhist, Hindu and Jain temples located in the Indian state of Maharashtra. These caves, built between the 6th and 10th centuries AD, are considered a remarkable example of religious harmony as they demonstrate the coexistence of Buddhism, Hinduism and Jainism in ancient India. The caves feature elaborate sculptures and carvings, including depictions of deities, mythical creatures, and scenes from Hindu epics such as the Mahabharata and Ramayana. The Kailasha Temple, a monolithic structure carved out of a single rock, is the largest cave temple in Ellora and considered one of the greatest rock-cut temples in the world. The Ellora Caves are a UNESCO World Heritage Site and a popular tourist destination in India.  The Ellora Caves remained largely untouched during Aurangzeb's reign, and continued to be a place of religious worship for centuries afterwards.  It is possible that some damage may have been inflicted on the Ellora Caves during the many wars and battles that took place in the region during Aurangzeb's rule. However, such damage would have likely been limited and the caves were still well-preserved for future generations to enjoy.  It's mesmerizing to enjoy such prestigious and rich in culture place engraved from ancient times.
